{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"0702754d-fcaa-48e5-9a99-57250bf81c62","content":"Your project is small — just one file. Here's what I found:\n\n**Untestable static dependencies in `my_app/views.py`:**\n\n| Line | Call | Issue |\n|------|------|-------|\n| 3 | `datetime.now()` | Hard-coded clock — can't control time in tests |\n\n**Recommendation:** Use Django's `django.utils.timezone.now()` instead, which you can mock with [`freezegun`](https://github.com/spulec/freezegun) or `unittest.mock.patch`:\n\n```python\nfrom django.utils import timezone\n\ndef index(request):\n    now = timezone.now()\n    return render(request, 'index.html', {'time': now})\n```\n\nThen in tests:\n```python\nfrom unittest.mock import patch\nfrom django.utils import timezone\n\n@patch('my_app.views.timezone.now')\ndef test_index(self, mock_now):\n    mock_now.return_value = datetime(2026, 1, 1)\n    # ...\n```\n\nThis is the only static dependency in the project. The fix is straightforward — swap `datetime.now()` for `timezone.now()` (which is also timezone-aware, a Django best practice).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"45564d72-1860-4e3d-b842-ec076bde5792","outputTokens":294,"requestId":"1BCA:234573:AADF6B:C1A660:6A03EE49"},"id":"22637dfc-8e4d-410e-a44b-8344a0093564","timestamp":"2026-05-13T03:21:52.334Z","parentId":"430f989b-0095-4a99-a778-dd5997afd981"}
